Blood on the Pine
A Skyrim Investigation Mystery for 5-6 Players (Apprentice Tier)
Estimated Play Time: 4-5 hours
 Party Size: 5-6 players
 Difficulty: Scaled for Apprentice Tier (1-2 AP)
 Reward: 1000 Gold per player, one powerful and two moderate enchanted items, and 1 Advancement Point.

Adventure Summary
The party's growing reputation has reached the grim hold of Falkreath. They are summoned by the Jarl's steward to investigate a series of bizarre disappearances where victims vanish from locked rooms without a trace. The party must act as detectives, piecing together clues from a terrified town to uncover a sophisticated coven of Cyrodiilic vampires. Their investigation will culminate in infiltrating the vampire's lair, where forensic evidence and documentary clues reveal the psychological profile and tactical weaknesses needed to confront the coven's masterΓÇöan ancient and charismatic vampire who sees the people of Falkreath not as prey, but as a resource to be managed.

Optional Rule: The Stages of Vampirism 
This adventure features combat with vampires, and with that comes the risk of infection. For groups who want to explore this classic trope, use the following three-stage progression. Contracting vampirism is a transformative event, a high-stakes personal arc that offers intoxicating power at a terrible price.
The Infection Event: The Predator's Mercy
When a player character is reduced to 0 HP by a vampire's natural attack (Claws), the creature does not simply leave them to die. It seizes the opportunity to feed and create a new fledgling.
The Narrative: Instead of falling unconscious, the character is grappled and pulled down. The last thing they see is the vampire's fangs descending towards their neck.
The Final Struggle: The character is not helpless. On their next turn, they can make one final, desperate attempt to fight off their attacker. This is a Hard (-2) Might roll.
On a Success: They shove the vampire away at the last second, avoiding infection. They remain at 0 HP and are dying.
On a Failure: The fangs sink deep. The curse enters their blood. They fall unconscious but are now stable at 0 HP. They have contracted Sanguinare Vampiris.

The Three Stages of Undeath
Stage 1: Sanguinare Vampiris (The Fever)
This is the initial stage, lasting for the remainder of the current adventure.
A burning fever racks the character's body. Their blood is at war with itself, and the curse grants them a desperate, feverish strength even as it ravages them.
Dramatic Effects:
Feverish Strength: The character feels a surge of unnatural power. They gain a +2 bonus to their Might Target Number.
Aversion to Divinity: The character's body rejects all forms of divine magic. Healing spells cast on them have no effect. They can only regain HP through potions, rest, or other non-divine means.
Roleplaying Cues: The character is visibly unwell, sweating and pale. They feel a gnawing hunger that normal food cannot satisfy and are plagued by visceral nightmares of hunting and feeding.
The Cure:
At this stage, the curse is a virulent disease. It can be cured by any standard Cure Disease Potion or by receiving a blessing from a priest at any temple. This must be done during the downtime between adventures.

Stage 2: Nascent Vampire (The Hunger)
This stage begins if the character starts a new adventure without having cured the disease.
The fever has broken, replaced by a chilling emptiness. The character is no longer sick; they are fundamentally changing. The Hunger is now a constant companion, demanding to be fed.
Dramatic Effects:
Predator's Cunning: The character's senses sharpen to a supernatural degree. They gain a +2 bonus to their Agility Target Number.
The Thirst: The character's mortal nature is fading. They no longer benefit from food, drink, or normal rest. They do not regain HP or FP from a Short or Long Rest. The only way to replenish their strength is by feeding.
Feeding: Once per adventure, as a Major Action on a willing, grappled, or unconscious humanoid, the character can feed. Doing so immediately restores all of their lost HP and FP.


Sunlight Sickness: Direct sunlight is now agonizing. The character has -2 to ALL their Stat Scores (Target Numbers) while in sunlight.
Roleplaying Cues: The character's skin has become pale, their canines slightly more pronounced. They find the presence of mortals both alluring and irritating.
The Cure:
A simple cure is impossible. The curse has bonded to their soul. Curing it requires a dedicated quest, such as seeking out Falion in Morthal to perform his dangerous soul-cleansing ritual.

Stage 3: Fledgling Vampire (The Beast)
This stage begins if the character starts another adventure as a Nascent Vampire.
The transformation is complete. The character is a true vampire, an undead predator. They have access to immense power, but their humanity hangs by a thread, and they must now bear the full weight of their curse.
Dramatic Effects:
Vampire Lord's Power: The character chooses one of their four core stats (Might, Agility, Magic, or Guile). That stat is permanently increased by +2.
Vampiric Drain: Their unarmed attacks are now considered magical weapons that deal 4 damage. When they deal damage with this attack, they heal for half the amount.
The Hunger Unbound: The character no longer benefits from mortal sustenance or rest. They do not regain HP or FP from a Short or Long Rest. The only way to replenish their strength is by feeding on the blood of the living.
Feeding (Major Action): The character can now attempt to feed on any willing, grappled, or unconscious humanoid at any time. A successful feed immediately restores all of their lost HP and FP. There is no longer a "once per adventure" limit.

The Curse's Price:
Revealed Predator: If the character is seen feeding by any non-vampiric NPC (guard, citizen, even a bandit), they are immediately and permanently Reviled in that hold.
Reviled Status: While in a hold where they are Reviled, the character cannot enter cities or settlements without being attacked on sight. All social interactions with non-vampire NPCs in that region automatically fail and become hostile.

Sunlight's Scourge: Direct sunlight is now lethal. At the start of their turn in sunlight, the character takes 4 irreducible damage as their flesh burns and smokes.
Fire's Fury: The character's undead flesh is highly flammable. They take double damage from all sources of fire.
Roleplaying Cues: Their eyes now have a faint, predatory glow in the dark. Their connection to mortal society feels distant, like a memory of a past life. The Hunger is a constant, dominant thought.
The Cure:
The character is no longer a mortal with a curse; they are a cursed being. A cure is the stuff of legend and would require an epic, multi-adventure quest that could form the basis of an entire campaign arc.

GM's Note: Becoming a vampire is a major narrative event. Be sure to discuss this possibility with your player. This mechanic is designed to create exciting stories of struggle and consequence, so ensure the player is on board with this potential direction for their character's arc.


Part I: Dead Man's Drink (The Hook)
Arriving in Falkreath
Read Aloud: "As you approach Falkreath along the old forest road, something feels wrong. The town that usually bustles with lumber trade and travelers is eerily quiet. The great pines that surround the settlement seem to lean in, casting long shadows even in midday. The scent of fresh-cut wood that normally permeates the air is absent, replaced by the smell of damp earth and something elseΓÇöfear, thick and cloying.
At the town gates, a single guard eyes you with a mixture of suspicion and desperate hope. 'State your business,' he says, hand resting on his sword hilt. 'We're not taking in refugees, and if you're here to trade lumber, the mills are closed.' His voice cracks slightly on the last word, betraying his professional demeanor."
Initial Interaction:
 If the party asks what's wrong or mentions they're adventurers, the guard's posture shifts from hostile to relieved: "Adventurers? Gods above, finally. You need to speak with Nenya, the Jarl's steward. She's been... well, she's at Dead Man's Drink. Been there for days, waiting for someone like you to show up."
Setting Expectations:
 The guard will not provide details about the disappearancesΓÇöhe's clearly been ordered not to spread panic. He'll only say: "People have gone missing. The steward will explain. Just... watch yourself. Lock your doors at night."

Entering Dead Man's Drink
Read Aloud: "Dead Man's Drink sits at the heart of Falkreath's small commercial district, its weathered sign creaking in the constant breeze. As you push open the heavy wooden door, the warmth and firelight should be welcoming, but instead, the atmosphere hits you like a physical weight.
The common room is perhaps a third fullΓÇöa poor showing for midday in a trading town. What few patrons are present huddle over their drinks, speaking in hushed whispers and casting furtive glances at the door every time it opens. A group of lumberjacks sits in the corner, their axes and tools untouched beside them, staring into their mugs with the hollow-eyed look of men who've stopped working but don't know what else to do.
The innkeeper, a weary-looking Nord woman, forces a smile that doesn't reach her eyes. 'Welcome to Dead Man's Drink,' she says, the traditional greeting sounding more like a warning than an invitation. 'Will you be needing rooms? Fair warningΓÇöwe lock the doors at sundown. No exceptions.'
At a corner table, away from the windows, sits a Dark Elf woman in fine but travel-worn clothing. Dark circles shadow her eyes, and a stack of untouched paperwork sits beside her. She's watching the door with an intensity that suggests she's been waiting for someone specific. When she sees you enterΓÇöclearly armed, clearly capableΓÇöher posture shifts. She rises slowly, studying each of you with the calculating gaze of someone who needs to know if you're the solution to her problem or just another complication."

The Quest Giver: Nenya
Stats: Guile 15, Might 10
Nenya is the pragmatic steward running the hold while her Jarl is preoccupied with himself. She has no time for superstition, only for results. She's been in Falkreath for three weeks since the disappearances began, and the strain is showing.
GM's Toolkit: Roleplaying Nenya
Demeanor: Exhausted, professional, and utterly pragmatic. She's past the point of pleasantries. She views the party as a tool to solve a problemΓÇöa very necessary tool, but a tool nonetheless. She's interviewed dozens of "concerned citizens" and "helpful locals" who've wasted her time with wild theories and gossip. She needs professionals.
Physical Presence: She moves with the precision of someone running on sheer willpower. Her robes are immaculate despite obvious travel wear. She keeps her hands flat on the table to stop them from trembling with exhaustion. When she speaks, her voice is controlled, but there's an edge of desperation underneath.
Key Dialogue Prompts:
Opening (as party approaches):
 "I am Nenya, steward to Jarl Siddgeir of Falkreath Hold. You have the look of capable peopleΓÇöadventurers, mercenaries, problem-solvers. I'm told Maven Black-Briar spoke highly of you after the business in Thornheart Grove." (She's done her research. This is a testΓÇöcan you handle work that requires discretion and competence?)
If asked about Maven:
 "I maintain certain... professional relationships across Skyrim. Maven's network is extensive, and when I needed capable people who weren't localΓÇöpeople who could investigate without being paralyzed by fear or prejudiceΓÇöyour names came up. She said you were professionals. Right now, Falkreath needs professionals more than it needs heroes."
If asked about the Jarl:
 "Jarl Siddgeir is... concerned with matters of state. He has delegated this matter to me." (A long pause, then with barely concealed contempt) "You will report to me. I am the one who authorized the payment, and I am the one who will evaluate your success."
If the party asks what happened:
 (She slides a piece of parchment across the tableΓÇöa list of names)
 "Four people. Gone. Vanished from locked rooms in the dead of night without a trace. No signs of struggle. No witnesses. No ransom demands. No bodies. The town guard has theories. All of them useless. The townspeople have theories. All of them ridiculous. What I need are facts."
If asked about the guard's investigation:
 "Guard Captain Valdemar is a competent soldier. He knows how to handle bandits and drunken brawls. But this?" (She gestures at the list) "He's out of his depth. He sees bandits in every shadow because that's what he knows how to fight. I need investigators, not soldiers."
If the party haggles for more money:
 (She closes her eyes briefly, as if summoning patience)
 "Eight hundred gold per person is what the hold can currently afford. Our primary industryΓÇölumberΓÇöhas ground to a halt. Half the workers won't leave their homes. The mill owners are considering relocating to Riften. If you succeed, the gratitude of this townΓÇöand my personal recommendation to every Jarl in SkyrimΓÇöwill be worth far more than coin. Succeed, and you will be rewarded accordingly. Fail, and there won't be a hold left to pay you anyway."
If asked for theories:
 "I deal in facts, not speculation. The facts are: four people disappeared from four different locations, all at night, all from locked rooms. The facts are: the town is paralyzed with fear. The facts are: if this continues for another week, Falkreath will be a ghost town. I don't care if it's Daedra, ghosts, vampires, or the Emperor himself wearing a mask. Find them. Stop them. Bring this town back from the brink."
If asked about the victims:
 "KustΓÇöblacksmith's apprentice, young, strong, skilled with metalwork. HertΓÇölumberjack from Half-Moon Mill, married she has a young daughter. The SalviansΓÇöan elderly merchant couple from Cyrodiil, here to close one final deal before retiring. All good people. All contributing members of the community. Whatever took them chose them deliberately."

What Nenya Provides
The Contract: She slides a sealed document across the tableΓÇöa Jarl's Writ granting the party official authority to:
Question any citizen of Falkreath Hold
Access crime scenes and private property relevant to the investigation (with appropriate discretion)
Requisition reasonable supplies from town merchants (within reason)
Call upon the town guard for support (though she makes it clear they're more likely to hinder than help)
The Payment Offer:
 "Eight hundred gold each upon successful resolution. The Jarl has authorized me to pay an additional two hundred gold per person from the hold's emergency reserves if you work swiftly. Time is a factor. I don't know why, but I feel it in my bones. Whatever is happening, it's building to something."
The Victims' Information:
 She provides a more detailed written report:
Kust (Age 19): Apprenticed to Lod the blacksmith. Disappeared five nights ago from his room above the forge. Door locked from inside. Master Lod found the room empty at dawn.
Hert (Age 34): Lumberjack, wife of Hern, mother to Elina (age 6). Disappeared eight nights ago from her home at Half-Moon Mill. Husband woke to find her gone, bedroom door still latched.
Salvian Couple (Ages 61 and 58): Merchants from Cyrodiil. Disappeared three nights ago from their rented room at Dead Man's Drink. Innkeeper Valga found the room empty when they didn't come down for breakfast. Door locked, window latched.
Her Warning:
 "The town is frightened. People will talkΓÇötoo much or too little, depending on their temperament. Separate truth from fear. The guard will likely interfere or dismiss your methods as 'outsider nonsense.' Work around them. And..." (she hesitates, clearly uncomfortable with what she's about to say) "...lock your doors at night. All of you. Whatever is doing this moves silently, and it hasn't been stopped by locks so far, but it's all we have."

Establishing the Stakes
Read Aloud (as party accepts the contract):
 "Nenya's shoulders drop slightly, the first sign of relief you've seen. 'Thank you,' she says quietly. Then, louder, to the room: 'These people are working for the hold. You will cooperate with them fully.' The lumberjacks and other patrons look up, hope flickering in their eyes for the first time.
The innkeeper, Valga, nods gratefully. 'You'll have rooms here, no charge. Meals too. Anything you need.' She lowers her voice. 'Please. My nephew was one of them. The Salvians. Good people. I keep thinking I'll hear them coming down for breakfast...'
As you take in the weight of their hopeΓÇöand the very real fear underlying itΓÇöthe sun begins its descent toward the horizon. The shadows in the room grow longer. Someone hastily lights more candles. The lumberjacks start gathering their things to leave before dark. The town is preparing for another night of terror, and you are now responsible for ending it."

Optional: First Night in Falkreath
GM Note: If you want to establish atmosphere before the investigation begins, you can run a short scene of the party's first night in Falkreath.
Read Aloud (that evening):
 "The sun sets over Falkreath with an unnatural swiftness, or perhaps it just feels that way. You hear the sound of doors being barred, shutters being closed, locks being checked and rechecked. By the time full darkness falls, the streets are empty. Not a soul moves outside.
From your rooms at Dead Man's Drink, you can hear every creak of the old building settling, every whisper of wind through the pines. The silence is oppressiveΓÇöno drunken singing, no late-night conversations, not even the sounds of the town guard on patrol. Just silence, and the feeling of a town holding its breath, waiting to see who will be gone in the morning.
Somewhere in the distance, a dog howlsΓÇöa long, mournful sound that's abruptly cut short."
GM Note: This is purely atmospheric. Nothing happens to the party on their first nightΓÇöthey're protected by narrative importance and the fact that Valerius is wary of obvious adventurers. But the fear should be palpable.

Part II: The Whispering Town (The Investigation)
The town feels cursed; food tastes like ash, and a sense of being watched is pervasive. The party must navigate a web of clues, false leads, and misdirection to identify the true perpetrator.
Investigation Structure: Two Acts
Act A: Prove Supernatural Involvement
 The party must establish that the disappearances are not mundane crimes (banditry, fleeing debts) but supernatural predation.
Act B: Identify the Perpetrator
 Multiple suspects emerge. The party must follow the evidence to identify the true culprit: Lord Valerius Caelus.

Act A: The Impossible Disappearances
Investigation Goal: Prove This Is Supernatural
The town guard and many citizens believe the victims simply fled or were taken by bandits. The party must prove the disappearances are impossible by mundane means.
The Clue Web
1. The Crime Scene (The Salvians' Room) - Proving the Impossible
The inn room the merchant couple rented is sealed by town guard. Nenya provides the key.
Read Aloud: "The room is pristine in an unnatural way. The bed is made with military precision, clothes are folded and packed as if for immediate departure, yet a half-eaten meal sits on the table, the bread still soft. The single window is latched tight from the inside, and there's not so much as a scuff mark on the floor."
Investigation Discovery Process
Clue #1 - The Locked Room (Forensic):
 A Standard Guile roll to examine the room reveals the door and window were both locked from the inside. The door's lock shows no signs of tampering. The window latch is dusty and clearly hasn't been opened in days.
The Deduction: The couple did not leave through any normal means. This rules out bandits, kidnappers, or voluntary departure.
Clue #2 - The Interrupted Meal (Behavioral):
 A Standard Guile roll notices the half-eaten meal is significant. The bread is still soft, the cheese hasn't hardened, the wine hasn't fully oxidized. This happened mere hours before discovery, yet no one heard anything.
The Deduction: Whatever took them was silent and sudden. They had no time to cry out or struggle.
Clue #3 - The Scent (Forensic - Supernatural Evidence):
 A Standard Guile roll reveals a faint, sweet, cloying scent that seems to calm the mind even as it unsettles the soul. It's floral but wrong somehow, like flowers that bloom in graveyards.
The Deduction: This is not natural. Something magical was present here.
Clue #4 - The Dust (Forensic - Supernatural Evidence):
 A Standard Guile roll reveals near the door, almost invisible unless one is looking for it, a smudge of fine, grey dust. It's not road dustΓÇöit's dry, ancient, like soil from a grave that hasn't been opened in decades.
The Deduction: Whatever entered came from somewhere old and buried. Combined with the sweet scent, this points to something undead or necromantic.
Clue #5 - The Magic (Forensic - Supernatural Evidence):
 A Standard Magic roll reveals lingering traces of two distinct magical schools:
Illusion magic hangs in the air like a lullaby, designed to calm and soothe.
Alteration magic feels ethereal and misty, as if something solid became incorporeal.
The Deduction: The perpetrator used magic to pacify the victims (Illusion) and bypass the locked door (Alteration - likely a Mist Form or Ethereal Passage effect).
GM Note: This is the crucial scene. Players must gather at least 3 of these 5 clues to conclusively prove supernatural involvement.

2. The Guard's Dead End (The Official Failure)
The town guard, led by a pragmatic but unimaginative captain, has their own theory.
Scene Description: The party can find Guard Captain Valdemar at the barracks or on patrol. He's a competent soldier but thinks like oneΓÇöevery problem has a straightforward solution.
Valdemar's Theory (The False Lead #1):
 "It's bandits. Has to be. Probably the ones up in the hillsΓÇöthey've been getting bolder. The locked room? Professional work. They picked the lock, took the couple, re-locked it from outside. It's been done before."
The Problem with His Theory:
 If players present the dust, the scent, or the magical residue, Valdemar dismisses it: "I'm a soldier, not a mage. I deal in what I can see and touch. Show me a bandit, I'll arrest them. Show me 'grave dust,' and I'll show you road dirt."
What He Can Provide:
Confirms all four victims disappeared from locked rooms
Provides a list of recent bandit activity (all far from town, none matching the sophistication)
Mentions the Salvians were wealthy merchantsΓÇö"prime targets for thieves"
GM Note: Valdemar is not malicious, just out of his depth. His bandit theory is plausible enough to be a red herring but falls apart under scrutiny.

3. The Witnesses Who Saw Nothing (Establishing a Pattern)
The party can interview stable hands, innkeepers, and neighbors near each disappearance site.
Universal Testimony (Standard Guile roll to gather):
"I was right there. I should have heard somethingΓÇöa scream, a struggle, footsteps. Nothing."
"It's like they just... vanished into thin air."
"The room was locked from inside. I checked it myself before I called the guards."
Incidental Detail - The Dog (Clue #6 - Behavioral):
 At the stables, a stable hand mentions: "Strangest thing... Kust's dog was with him that night. Big, mean hound, protective as they come. Whatever happened, that dog didn't make a sound. Found him the next morning, just lying by the forge, whimpering. Wouldn't eat for two days."
The Deduction: Even animals were affected. This suggests powerful Illusion magic that can suppress natural alarm responses.

Act A Resolution: The Supernatural Conclusion
If the party presents their evidence to Nenya (or discusses it among themselves), they can make a Standard Guile or Magic roll to synthesize their findings:
On Success:
 "This is not banditry. The locked rooms, the grave dust, the magical residue, the unnatural silenceΓÇöthis is a supernatural predator. Something that can bypass physical barriers, suppress alarm, and operate with complete stealth. Most likely vampirism or powerful necromancy."
GM Note: This conclusion opens Act BΓÇöthe search for the specific perpetrator.

Act B: The Hunt for the Predator
Investigation Goal: Identify the Culprit
Multiple suspects emerge, each with connections to the victims. The party must follow the evidence to identify Lord Valerius Caelus.
The Suspect Pool
Suspect #1: Dengeir of Stuhn (The Paranoid Former Jarl)
Who He Is: The former Jarl of Falkreath, now elderly and increasingly paranoid. He lives in his manor, ranting about conspiracies.
Why He's Suspicious:
He's obsessed with "dark forces" infiltrating Falkreath
He has a history of accusing people of being vampire thralls
He knew all four victims personally (small town)
His manor is old, filled with ancient artifacts and books on necromancy
The Evidence Against Him (Red Herring):
 A Standard Guile roll while investigating his manor (requires clever entry or permission) reveals:
A collection of anti-vampire texts and blessed weapons
Notes about "monitoring suspicious newcomers"
A list with all four victims' names circled
The Exoneration (Clue #7 - Testimonial):
 If players question Dengeir directly and succeed on a Hard (-2) Guile (Persuasion) roll, he reveals: "I've been watching the new 'lord' at the Hall of the Honored. Valerius Caelus. Moved here six months ago. Claims to be a scholar, but I've lived eighty wintersΓÇöI know a vampire when I see one. Problem is, no one believes a paranoid old man. I was trying to gather proof."
Alternative Discovery:
 His steward can reveal (Standard Guile roll): "The master's been investigating that new lord. Spends his nights watching the graveyard. Says the man never comes out during the day."
GM Note: Dengeir is a false lead who actually points toward the real culprit. His paranoia makes him easy to dismiss, which is why no one believed him.

Suspect #2: Mathies and Indara Caerellia (The Struggling Innkeepers)
Who They Are: A married couple who run the Falkreath lumber mill (not Half-Moon Mill). Business has been terrible, and they're drowning in debt.
Why They're Suspicious:
Kust owed them money for lumber deliveries
The Salvians stayed at an inn they have financial ties to
They've been seen arguing violently about their debts
Mathies has a background as a hunterΓÇöhe knows how to move silently
The Evidence Against Them (Red Herring):
 A Standard Guile roll while investigating their business records (town hall or their home) reveals:
Significant debts to multiple creditors
Notes about "final solutions" and "desperate measures"
Records showing Kust owed them 200 gold
The Exoneration (Clue #8 - Testimonial with Alibi):
 If players confront them and succeed on a Standard Guile (Persuasion) roll: "Yes, we were desperate! But not desperate enough to murder. The night Kust disappeared, we were at the jarl's longhouseΓÇöyou can check. Siddgeir's steward will confirm. We were begging for a loan extension until dawn."
Alternative Discovery:
 Nenya's records confirm their alibi: "The Caerellias were in my office until sunrise the night of Kust's disappearance. I remember because I finally agreed to extend their deadline just to get them to leave."
GM Note: The Caerellias are a red herring based on financial motive. Their desperation is real, but their alibis are ironclad.

Suspect #3: Lord Valerius Caelus (The True Culprit)
Who He Is: A wealthy newcomer who moved to Falkreath six months ago, claiming to be a scholar of Nordic history. He purchased the Hall of the Honored as a "private archive" and rarely leaves his estate.
Why He's Suspicious:
He's reclusive and never seen during daylight
All four victims had business dealings with him
He pays well but demands absolute secrecy about his commissions
The Hall of the Honored is a sealed mausoleum in the graveyard
The Evidence Against Him (The Convergence):
Clue #9 - The Economic Connection (Documentary):
 At the Forge: Lod's grief is palpable, but a Standard Guile (Persuasion) roll gets him to share Kust's ledger.
"Fail Forward" Mechanic: If the party fails, Lod throws them out. They can return that night and attempt a Hard (-2) Agility (Sneak) or Guile (Lockpicking) roll to break in.
The Ledger: Details a large commission from Lord Valerius Caelus for pure silver fittings for the Hall of the Honored. A key note reads: "Master Lod insisted I order three extra billets of pure silver. He says you never know when a client will change their mind, or when you'll need a way to put down a monster."
GM Note: This is the first direct link to Valerius and provides a future weapon (silver).
Clue #10 - The Lumber Connection (Testimonial):
 At Half-Moon Mill: Hern is softer than Lod, more likely to break down. He gives the party the half-finished wooden bird for his daughter Elina.
"Hert was hired by Lord Valerius Caelus. Big jobΓÇödeliver choice pine lumber to the Hall of the Honored. She was so excited. Said the pay would let us fix the mill's wheel. She never came home."
GM Note: This is the second confirmation of Valerius, applying the Rule of Three.
Clue #11 - The Merchant Connection (Documentary):
 Back at the Salvians' room: A shipping manifest confirms a sale to Lord Valerius Caelus, with goods delivered to the Hall of the Honored. Tucked inside is a personal note to their son in Cyrodiil about their "final deal" before retirement.
GM Note: This is the third confirmation, conclusively linking Valerius to all victims.
Clue #12 - The Nocturnal Observation (Behavioral):
 If players ask around town about Valerius (Standard Guile roll), they gather consistent testimony:
"Never seen him during the day. Always sends his servants for supplies."
"Paid in old Imperial gold. The kind you don't see anymore."
"Polite enough, but there's something... off. Like talking to someone wearing a mask."
Clue #13 - Dengeir's Warning (Testimonial):
 If players spoke with Dengeir, he explicitly warns them: "Valerius Caelus is a vampire. I'd stake my remaining years on it. Watch the Hall of the Honored at nightΓÇöyou'll see."

4. The Cryptic Warning (The Challenge & The Deadline)
Once the party has identified Valerius as their primary suspect, they can investigate the Hall of the Honored.
Read Aloud: "The Hall of the Honored stands at the heart of Falkreath's ancient graveyard, a weathered stone structure that serves as a monument to the hold's most distinguished dead. The heavy stone door is seamlessly sealed, humming with a quiet magical energy. But what catches your attention is not the door itself, but what lies at its base.
A single, perfect Nightshade blossom sits precisely centered on the door's threshold. The flower is impossibly fresh, its dark petals seeming to absorb the dim light around it. There's an unnatural perfection to it that makes your skin crawl. Tucked delicately between the petals is a small piece of parchment, the paper fine and expensive."
The Note - Clue #14 (Documentary):
 Written in elegant, flowing script: "My collection nears completion. The preservation ritual will be finished under the new moon's gaze. It is a pity you will not be here to witness the culmination of my work. The vintage must be sealed before it spoils."
The Revelation: A Standard Guile or Magic roll reveals the new moon is tomorrow night. This isn't just a tauntΓÇöit's a deadline.
The Chill - Clue #15 (Behavioral):
 As the party reads the note, a character with the highest passive Guile feels a sudden, inexplicable chill, as if unseen eyes are watching them from the shadows between the gravestones.
GM Note: This establishes that Valerius knows about the investigation and is confident enough to taunt them. It also creates time pressure.

Act B Resolution: The Identification
The party can now confidently conclude:
Lord Valerius Caelus is the perpetrator
His base is the Hall of the Honored
He is likely a vampire (based on nocturnal behavior, grave dust, supernatural abilities, and Dengeir's warning)
He has been kidnapping skilled workers for some unknown purpose
They have until tomorrow night to stop him
The Entrance
The party attempts to open the sealed door. Various methods might work, but the intended solution:
The Riddle: A Standard Magic roll to examine the door reveals it's sealed with a ward keyed to a specific phrase. The ward is designed to open when the master's name is spoken.
The Solution: Speaking "Valerius Caelus" before the door causes the magical seal to hiss and retract, allowing entry.
Alternative Solutions:
Brute Force: A Very Hard (-4) Might roll to break the ancient stone
