Phase 1: Social Combat (Optional - Recommended)
Valerius doesn't immediately attack. Instead, he studies the party with the calculating gaze of a predator who has all the time in the world.
GM Note: This phase allows players to use their investigation discoveries. Each argument they counter successfully based on the clues they found grants them a tactical advantage in Phase 2.
Valerius's Opening Arguments
The Pragmatic Argument:
 "So, the bloodhounds have finally followed the scent to its source. Tell me, how much is Maven Black-Briar paying you for this? Ah, you think I don't know? I make it my business to know about anyone who might interfere with my work. You chose to work for a criminal who destroys lives for profit, who poisons wells and murders competitors. I am an artist; she is a butcher. Tell me again who the monsters are."
The Mirror Argument:
 "You ransacked the private room of a grieving family while their son waits for word from them in another city. You threatened a broken man for his dead apprentice's private journal. You stalked a widower through his grief. Your methods are as ruthless as mineΓÇömine are simply more permanent and infinitely more purposeful."
The Salvation Argument:
 "The blacksmith's boy? Without his master's guidance, he would have died in some tavern brawl within a year. The lumberjack? Her husband will drink himself to death without her, leaving their daughter an orphan. I offered them eternity, purpose, preservation of their talents. What do you offer them? A return to grinding poverty and meaningless death?"
GM Guide for Player Responses
The party must make Hard (-2) Guile rolls to counter his arguments. However, if they use specific clues discovered during their investigation, the difficulty is reduced or the result is enhanced:
Using "The Mortal Heart" (Clues #10, #15):
 If players reference his family: "Your family loved you as a man, not as the thing you've become. Do you think Livia and Marcus would recognize the monster wearing their husband and father's face? You didn't preserve themΓÇöyou lost them. And now you're trying to fill that void with slaves."
Effect: Automatic success on the Guile roll. Valerius is visibly shaken, losing his composure.
If players also found the psychology book (Clue #16): This becomes a CRITICAL success. Valerius is so emotionally devastated that he loses his first Major Action in Phase 2 as he struggles to regain composure.
Using "The Tyrant's Delusion" (Clues #11, #13):
 If players reference the cages or work orders: "You call yourself a curator, but you built livestock pens. You write 'specimen acquired' and 'resource secured.' You don't see peopleΓÇöyou see tools. Your journal is filled with philosophy, but your actions are those of a slave master."
Effect: Standard difficulty becomes Easy (+2). On success, Valerius cannot use his "Dominate Will" ability on that character for the entire fightΓÇöthey've seen through his manipulation.
Using "The Collector's Method" (Clues #9, #12, #14, #17):
 If players describe his preservation process: "We've seen your 'preservation.' The magical stasis that reduces people to near-death. The apparatus that drains their life force. The compulsion magic you weave into everything you create. This isn't artΓÇöit's necromancy. You're not preserving talent; you're creating corpse-puppets."
Effect: The party gains tactical knowledge. All party members gain +2 to saves against his Illusion magic for the entire fight.
Mechanical Resolution
Each successful counter (or automatic success from using clues) causes Valerius to become more agitated. After three successful counters, or one critical success from using "The Mortal Heart" + psychology book combo, his facade shatters completely and Phase 2 begins.
If players don't engage in social combat or fail all attempts, Phase 2 begins immediately with no advantages gained.

